    <article class="entrada">
        <div class="texto-entrada">
            <h1>Example 1</h1>
        </div>
        <p class="fw-mio2">
            Verify that the function [f(x)= y 1/x] is the solution of the differential equation [xy' +y =0]
            <br/>
            ㅤㅤㅤ<b>1)</b> We substitute y, y' into the differential equation to see that it satisfies the relationship.
            <br/>
                \[ y' = \frac{-1}{x^2} \]
                \[ y = \frac{1}{x} \]
            <br/>
            ㅤㅤㅤ<b>2)</b> Already having y, y' we substitute in the differential equation
            <br/>
                \[ xy'+y = x (\frac{-1}{x^2})+ \frac{1}{x} \]
                \[ = -\frac{1}{x}+\frac{1}{x}  \]
                \[ = 0  \]
        </p>
        <div class="texto-entrada">
            <h2></h2>
        </div>
    </article>
    <article class="entrada">
        <div class="texto-entrada">
            <h1>Example 2</h1>
        </div>
        <p class="fw-mio2">

            Check the function [f(x)= y = ¼-x^2] is a solution to the differential equation [dy / dx = 2xy^2] and determine at least one interval of solution.            <br/>
                <b>1)</b> We derive the function:
            <br/>
                \[ y = \frac{1}{4} - x^2  \]
                \[ \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{2x}{(4-x^2)^2}  \]
            <br/>
            ㅤㅤ<b>2)</b> Rewrite the equation and simplify.
            <br/>
                \[ \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{2x}{(4-x^2)^2}  \]
                \[ = 2x \frac{1}{(4-x^2)^2}\]
                \[ = 2x (\frac{1}{4-x^2})^2\]
                \[ = 2xy^2 \]
        </p>
